		{
			"name": "02B-Authentication-Flow",
			"description": "🔐 Authentication testing with ReqRes API - Learn 401 vs 403!",
			"item": [
				{
					"name": "📖 README - Start Here",
					"request": {
						"method": "GET",
						"header": [],
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/users/1",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["users", "1"]
						},
						"description": "# 🎓 Authentication Flow Tutorial\n\n## What You'll Learn\n\n1. **Login Flow** - Get JWT token\n2. **Token Storage** - Save to collection variable\n3. **Protected Requests** - Use saved token\n4. **Error Scenarios** - 401 vs 403\n\n## Order to Run\n\n1️⃣ **Login - Valid Credentials** → Get token\n2️⃣ **Get User Profile (With Token)** → Use token\n3️⃣ **Access Without Token (401)** → Missing auth\n4️⃣ **401 vs 403 Explained** → Understand difference\n\n## Key Concepts\n\n**401 Unauthorized**\n- \"Who are you?\" (Authentication failed)\n- Missing or invalid token\n- Solution: Login\n\n**403 Forbidden**\n- \"I know who you are, but you can't do this\" (Authorization failed)\n- Valid token but insufficient permissions\n- Solution: Need higher privileges\n\n## Interview Tip\n\n> \"I implement authentication testing by first logging in to get a JWT token, saving it to a collection variable, and reusing it across all protected endpoints. I test both positive scenarios (valid token) and negative scenarios (missing token returns 401, valid token with insufficient permissions returns 403).\"\n\n**Let's start! Run the requests below in order.** 👇"
					}
				},
				{
					"name": "1️⃣ Login - Valid Credentials",
					"event": [
						{
							"listen": "test",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"// ============================================",
									"// Step 1: Validate Login Success",
									"// ============================================",
									"pm.test('✅ Login successful (200)', function () {",
									"    pm.response.to.have.status(200);",
									"});",
									"",
									"// ============================================",
									"// Step 2: Extract and Save Token",
									"// ============================================",
									"pm.test('✅ Token received and saved', function () {",
									"    const jsonData = pm.response.json();",
									"    pm.expect(jsonData).to.have.property('token');",
									"    ",
									"    const token = jsonData.token;",
									"    pm.collectionVariables.set('bearerToken', token);",
									"    ",
									"    // Set expiration (1 hour from now)",
									"    const expiry = Date.now() + (60 * 60 * 1000);",
									"    pm.collectionVariables.set('tokenExpiry', expiry);",
									"    ",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('🎉 LOGIN SUCCESSFUL!');",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('Token:', token);",
									"    console.log('Expires:', new Date(expiry).toLocaleString());",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('✅ Token saved to collection variable');",
									"    console.log('✅ Now you can run protected endpoints!');",
									"});"
								]
							}
						}
					],
					"request": {
						"method": "POST",
						"header": [
							{
								"key": "Content-Type",
								"value": "application/json"
							}
						],
						"body": {
							"mode": "raw",
							"raw": "{\n    \"email\": \"eve.holt@reqres.in\",\n    \"password\": \"cityslicka\"\n}"
						},
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/login",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["login"]
						},
						"description": "**Purpose:** Login with valid credentials\n\n**What happens:**\n1. Send POST with email/password\n2. API returns JWT token\n3. Test script saves token to `{{bearerToken}}`\n4. Token is reused in all protected requests\n\n**Interview Talking Point:**\n\"This demonstrates the authentication flow. After successful login, I extract the JWT token from the response and save it to a collection variable using pm.collectionVariables.set(). This allows all subsequent requests to automatically include the token, making tests scalable and maintainable.\""
					}
				},
				{
					"name": "2️⃣ Login - Invalid Credentials",
					"event": [
						{
							"listen": "test",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"pm.test('✅ Invalid credentials rejected (400)', function () {",
									"    pm.response.to.have.status(400);",
									"});",
									"",
									"pm.test('✅ Error message provided', function () {",
									"    const jsonData = pm.response.json();",
									"    pm.expect(jsonData).to.have.property('error');",
									"    console.log('Error message:', jsonData.error);",
									"});",
									"",
									"pm.test('✅ No token returned', function () {",
									"    const jsonData = pm.response.json();",
									"    pm.expect(jsonData).to.not.have.property('token');",
									"    console.log('✅ Security: No token leaked on failed login');",
									"});"
								]
							}
						}
					],
					"request": {
						"method": "POST",
						"header": [
							{
								"key": "Content-Type",
								"value": "application/json"
							}
						],
						"body": {
							"mode": "raw",
							"raw": "{\n    \"email\": \"wrong@email.com\",\n    \"password\": \"wrongpassword\"\n}"
						},
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/login",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["login"]
						},
						"description": "**Purpose:** Test negative scenario - invalid credentials\n\n**Expected:**\n- 400 Bad Request\n- Error message\n- No token returned\n\n**Interview Talking Point:**\n\"Testing negative scenarios is crucial. This validates that the API properly rejects invalid credentials and doesn't leak tokens. In my testing strategy, I always cover both happy paths and error cases.\""
					}
				},
				{
					"name": "3️⃣ Get User Profile (With Token)",
					"event": [
						{
							"listen": "prerequest",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"const token = pm.collectionVariables.get('bearerToken');",
									"",
									"if (!token) {",
									"    console.error('❌ No token found!');",
									"    console.error('👉 Please run \"1️⃣ Login - Valid Credentials\" first');",
									"} else {",
									"    console.log('✅ Token found:', token);",
									"    console.log('✅ Proceeding with authenticated request');",
									"}"
								]
							}
						},
						{
							"listen": "test",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"pm.test('✅ Authenticated request successful', function () {",
									"    pm.response.to.have.status(200);",
									"});",
									"",
									"pm.test('✅ Protected data retrieved', function () {",
									"    const jsonData = pm.response.json();",
									"    pm.expect(jsonData.data).to.have.property('id');",
									"    pm.expect(jsonData.data).to.have.property('email');",
									"    ",
									"    const user = jsonData.data;",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('✅ AUTHENTICATED REQUEST SUCCESSFUL');",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('User:', user.first_name, user.last_name);",
									"    console.log('Email:', user.email);",
									"    console.log('Token was automatically included in request!');",
									"});"
								]
							}
						}
					],
					"request": {
						"auth": {
							"type": "bearer",
							"bearer": [
								{
									"key": "token",
									"value": "{{bearerToken}}",
									"type": "string"
								}
							]
						},
						"method": "GET",
						"header": [],
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/users/2",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["users", "2"]
						},
						"description": "**Purpose:** Access protected resource using saved token\n\n**How it works:**\n1. Authorization tab set to \"Bearer Token\"\n2. Token value: `{{bearerToken}}` (from collection)\n3. Postman automatically adds: `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n\n**Interview Talking Point:**\n\"This demonstrates token reuse. After the initial login, all protected endpoints automatically include the Bearer token from our collection variable. This approach is scalable - I can run 100 requests and only need to login once. The token is automatically included in every request's Authorization header.\""
					}
				},
				{
					"name": "4️⃣ Access Without Token (401)",
					"event": [
						{
							"listen": "prerequest",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"console.log('🚫 Testing: Request WITHOUT Token');",
									"console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"console.log('This request intentionally has NO auth header');",
									"console.log('Expected: API will likely return 200 (ReqRes is lenient)');",
									"console.log('Real APIs would return: 401 Unauthorized');",
									"console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');"
								]
							}
						},
						{
							"listen": "test",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"pm.test('📚 Understanding 401 Unauthorized', function () {",
									"    // ReqRes doesn't enforce auth, but this explains the concept",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('📚 401 UNAUTHORIZED');",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    console.log('Meaning: \"Who are you?\"');",
									"    console.log('');",
									"    console.log('When you get 401:');",
									"    console.log('• Authentication failed');",
									"    console.log('• Missing token/credentials');",
									"    console.log('• Invalid token');",
									"    console.log('• Expired token');",
									"    console.log('');",
									"    console.log('Solution: Login to get valid token');",
									"    console.log('━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━');",
									"    ",
									"    pm.expect(pm.response.code).to.be.oneOf([200, 401]);",
									"});"
								]
							}
						}
					],
					"request": {
						"auth": {
							"type": "noauth"
						},
						"method": "GET",
						"header": [],
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/users/2",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["users", "2"]
						},
						"description": "**Purpose:** Demonstrate 401 Unauthorized scenario\n\n**Expected (in real APIs):**\n- 401 Unauthorized\n- Error: Missing authentication\n\n**Note:** ReqRes.in doesn't actually enforce authentication, so this returns 200. In production APIs, this would return 401.\n\n**Interview Talking Point:**\n\"401 Unauthorized means the server doesn't know who you are - authentication failed. This happens when the token is missing, invalid, or expired. It's different from 403 Forbidden, which means the server knows who you are but you don't have permission.\""
					}
				},
				{
					"name": "5️⃣ 401 vs 403 Explained",
					"event": [
						{
							"listen": "test",
							"script": {
								"exec": [
									"pm.test('📚 Understanding 401 vs 403', function () {",
									"    console.log(`",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"                    401 vs 403: KEY DIFFERENCE",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"",
									"🔴 401 UNAUTHORIZED",
									"   Question: \"WHO ARE YOU?\"",
									"   Problem: Authentication failed",
									"   ",
									"   Causes:",
									"   • Missing token/credentials",
									"   • Invalid token format",
									"   • Expired token",
									"   • Wrong username/password",
									"   ",
									"   HTTP Header: WWW-Authenticate",
									"   User Action: Login / Provide credentials",
									"   ",
									"   Example: Accessing API without token",
									"   ",
									"",
									"🟡 403 FORBIDDEN",
									"   Question: \"I KNOW WHO YOU ARE, BUT YOU CAN'T DO THIS\"",
									"   Problem: Authorization failed",
									"   ",
									"   Causes:",
									"   • Valid token but insufficient permissions",
									"   • User is not in correct role (not admin)",
									"   • Resource access restricted by policy",
									"   • IP address blocked",
									"   ",
									"   User Action: Request elevated privileges / different role",
									"   ",
									"   Example: Regular user accessing admin-only endpoint",
									"   ",
									"",
									"📊 COMPARISON TABLE",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"Aspect         | 401 Unauthorized        | 403 Forbidden",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"Meaning        | Who are you?            | You can't do this",
									"Issue          | Authentication failed   | Authorization failed",
									"Token Status   | Missing/Invalid         | Valid",
									"User Identity  | Unknown                 | Known",
									"Solution       | Login                   | Request permission",
									"Retry After?   | Yes (with valid token)  | No (need different role)",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"",
									"🎯 REAL-WORLD SCENARIOS",
									"",
									"Scenario 1: User tries to GET /api/profile without token",
									"→ Response: 401 Unauthorized",
									"→ Reason: Server doesn't know who you are",
									"→ Fix: Login and provide token",
									"",
									"Scenario 2: Regular user tries to DELETE /api/users/123",
									"→ Response: 403 Forbidden",
									"→ Reason: Server knows you're 'john_doe' but you're not admin",
									"→ Fix: Need admin role",
									"",
									"Scenario 3: Expired token used to access protected resource",
									"→ Response: 401 Unauthorized",
									"→ Reason: Token is invalid (expired)",
									"→ Fix: Refresh token or re-login",
									"",
									"",
									"💡 INTERVIEW TIP",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"When asked about authentication testing, mention both:",
									"",
									"\"In my API testing, I validate both authentication and authorization.",
									"I test that protected endpoints return 401 when accessed without",
									"valid credentials, and 403 when accessed with valid credentials",
									"but insufficient permissions. This ensures proper security controls.",
									"",
									"For example, I verify that regular users cannot access admin",
									"endpoints even with valid tokens - they should get 403, not 200.",
									"And requests without tokens should fail with 401 before even",
									"checking permissions.\"",
									"━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━",
									"    `);",
									"});"
								]
							}
						}
					],
					"request": {
						"method": "GET",
						"header": [],
						"url": {
							"raw": "{{authBaseUrl}}/users/1",
							"host": ["{{authBaseUrl}}"],
							"path": ["users", "1"]
						},
						"description": "**Purpose:** Educational request explaining 401 vs 403\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n**401 Unauthorized:**\n- \"Who are you?\"\n- Authentication failed\n- Missing/invalid/expired token\n- Solution: Login\n\n**403 Forbidden:**\n- \"I know who you are, but you can't do this\"\n- Authorization failed\n- Valid token but insufficient permissions\n- Solution: Need elevated privileges\n\n**Interview Tip:**\nAlways mention BOTH when discussing authentication testing. Show you understand the security model.\n\n**Example Answer:**\n\"I test authentication by verifying that requests without tokens return 401 Unauthorized. Then I test authorization by verifying that users with valid tokens but wrong roles get 403 Forbidden when accessing restricted resources. This ensures both layers of security are working correctly.\""
					}
				}
			]
		},
